				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Funny, I just tested the 52 fire pet to see if he equips two handers, he doesn't</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Oh wow I guess that was the one thing I didn't check for myself. I remember remarking to someone how much better he melees with his DS when they said I should get him a 2 hander and watch him hit harder. Guess I should have tested that myself too :( Thanks for pointing it out Dalren.
<br />

<br />
About the kiting thing. The whole point of a kiting group is to not have any members/pets get hit while the mob goes down due to low hp to mob hit ratio. Where I tested this was in that first GoDs zone where the big Turepta turtles are (forget name). We had druids charming the wolf-things and then running the rest of the animals around with the wolf pets. It was EASY to work around the root. In fact it worked really well. What happened was once the fire pet rooted it he would do one of two things:
<br />
1) he would sit back and cast spells and the druids and I were nuking anyways so root hardly lasted (and their pets had enough hp even if they didn't /pet back off)
<br />
2) he would rush into melee but do something I hadn't seen him do before. He would then cast his knockback spell immediately then the mob would be rooted and far away. The pet and I would continue to nuke the mob until dead. Often times when this happened the druids would go pick up another kiting target while the pet and I finished up the current mob.
<br />

<br />
I don't know how to do parses but I think I might be able to look it up.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
